< Text>
We were seated instantly. Got here at around 9am for breakfast. Our orders for drinks and food were taken almost as soon as we had decided. Food came in about 8min (yes I time those things) excellent. I had a machaca with eggs, rice & beans plate. It was perfect. After we had finished I forgot I had ordered flan. Asked for it and in a literal minute it was on my table. I cannot express how perfect the consistency of the flan was. I am a stickler for flan, too soft...you might as well call it a custard, too thick...you might as well call it a cake. I have no idea how people can fail at this but Mar y Tierra doesn't. Props.</Text>

Darby Cost</name>

<userid>101130404818641452672</userid>< user_name>
CanonRulesSaysGod< /user_name>
< date>
1563306026295</date>
<Rating>1</Rating>< text>
I was road tripping through the area and saw this place had a bunch of good reviews and a pretty stellar rating. It was a ghost town when I showed up, which for the time of day didnt seem too strange. the place was clean and the woman working that morning greeted us promptly. We got water to start and took a sec to look through the menu, nothing special, just your standard mexican restaurant fare. The woman brought out chips and pico, to start and the chips were horribly over cooked and came in odd shapes that made dipping very difficult as well as having a sort of stale taste to begin with. I ordered the special carnitas nachos with jalepenos added to them and a few chorizo street tacos, my companion ordered a bean and cheese burrito. Let the dissapointment begin...
There were no tantalizing smells of food getting prepared in the kitchen, no clanking of pans or sounds of fresh sausage sizzling, just the unashamed open and close of a microwave door while the woman sat in a stool by the front. When I received my nachos, I couldnt fricken believe it, the cheese sauce looked like yellow baby vommit separating from itself and watery, the carnitas were hard looking and a strange hue of greenish brown with this irridescense to the surface, and she had put whole pickled jalepenos and carrots over the top of them just coating my stale old nightmare nachos in vinegar. The presentation was bad, the taste was horrific and it wasnt even luke warm. After that got to the table I decided it was time to go. I couldnt imagine what the other food would be like if the nachos were ruined so badly. And like I guessed not even the chorizo deserved to be cooked fresh in her mind, she started bringing what looked like poorly cooked(in the first place whenever that was) leftovers and we got the hell outta there, I was shocked and taken by surprise that an establishment could be so terrible, so lifeless that the food would be that way, I felt bad, because she must be on here way out of the biz so I paid but it was almost 40 dollars for the aforementioned slop plus 1 beer and a bottled coke. Just crazy, never again! Dont send your friends or your enemies to Ricardas. Id have rather been punched in the face and saved my 40 bucks than to have burnt it in that dumpster.</text>

< review>
I first tried one of Ricarda's burritos 20 years ago, shortly after they opened. Since then, it has been the benchmark by which all burritos are measured. I'm not even slightly exaggerating. Go there. You won't be sorry.

The food is awesome, and the people are too. Ricarda will treat you like a lost family member--my brother and I referred to her as "Mama Ricarda".  We moved back to the East Coast a few years ago, but every time we are back in Northern California, a visit to Ricarda's is an essential part of the trip.</review>

<Text>Being a Southern Californian latina, and growing up with extensive knowledge with Mexican and Latino foods. I have to say that I'm very disappointed in the pricing and the quality of food that was given to me at Ricardas.
Menudo is $11.00 when it should be $8.00, (it's just broth and tri-tip) flavorless, and you can absolutely tell that it was sitting in a cauldron all day. It was luke-warm when it came to my table. Did not finish it.

The Carn√© Asada was old, bland and didn't have that fresh off the grill taste or feeling that asada is suppose to have.
I feel like the woman taking my order was taking advantage of the English speakers in her restaurant. Trying to upsale at every moment.

It makes me sad to see Mexican Americans loose pride and dignity in their cultural dishes, just because we are a consumerist country. The employees of Ricardas know that they are a minority in town and any dish will sell.

Don't waste your time here, way better places to eat in Bragg.
Im still dealing with a stomach ache from just soup and two tacos.</Text><Pictures>None</Pictures><Response>None< /Response><Gmap_id>0x8080355286c398bb:0x225acf33673837de< /Gmap_id></record>

< Text>
Disappointed, All Around.

I'm a big Chile Verde fan and was looking forward to a plate while visiting family in Fresno.

On the plate was meat, rice and beans. Plop, plop, plop... all average.
The Chile Verde flavor was good and  a lot of it... but the meat was gritty.

Most disappointing was the guacamole. Where you'd anticipate the primary ingredient to be avocado, Rosa Linda's was onion. It was the worst Guac I'd ever had... and at about $4 for the two tablespoons the insult was doubled.

Almost as disappointing were the chips served with my salsa and guacamole. Basically, corn tortillas cut and deep fried. I'm only guessing but they tasted like stale tortillas that were deep fired instead of thrown away.  These were just cold flavorless crunchy cardboard.

My two servers were pleasant and easily the best part of my experience.
But to Rosa Linda's, I say adios.<//Text>

< review>
Found this place online while looking for a good lunch place on vacation.  I had no idea we were going to hit a goldmine!  The burgers are some of the best I've ever had (probably in competition for the best I've ever had) and at $10.29 a burger + $3.50 or so for fries, we're  at $14-15 a meal!  For one of the best burgers of my life.  Again, goldmine.

Vibe feels like surfer meets Californian hipster.  Not my usual scene but between the owner who I can only describe as just plain ol friendly!  We did not feel out of place eating as a family one bit.  Seriously, give this place a go it is fantastic, with extremely reasonable prices. A++</review>

< Rating>
1<//Rating>
<review>I used to love Crazee Burger, The burger special was always great to get when you wanted a beer and a burger. That being said the last couple of times I have been there the burgers are under cooked. Last night my daughter and I went, I ordered the Jamaican, she got the Napoli Burger.  I clearly stated I wanted mine well done.

Burgers come out and both of them are really pink inside the burger. I put it down and was about to go complain, but my daughter decided she would just go ask them to recook it. 5 minutes goes by and the come back with the same burger. I bite into it and it looks cooked and tastes fine, so the chef goes on back. A few bites more and it is still pink in the middle. I couldn't finish my burger and I felt as though I could send it back 5 more times and the thing would still MOO at me. It made me sick, I ate maybe 5 bites of the whole burger.

My daughter couldn't eat hers either. We went home feeling unwell, and with empty stomachs. I for one will not be eating at Crazee Burger ever again.  It is as if they are cooking on high flames, and over cooking the outside and under cooking the insides. This is not the only time this has happened there, but the last time I thought it was just an accident. Well you don't under cook "well done" several times and chalk it up as a mistake.  IF you like raw meat then go to Crazee burger, otherwise you might want to avoid the place.<//review>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

A neighborhood staple. I've been going to Crazee Burger since before I even lived in North Park. I want to say my first time there was actually at the old location.

This place is tough to beat when it comes to getting a burger in the neighborhood. Ingredients always feel incredibly fresh and they know exactly what they're doing with flavor combos.

Can we talk about the fires? The fries are insane...way better than they have any right to be and enough to get you in the door even if everything else wasn't as good...but everything else IS as good. Highly recommended for when you're feeling "I want a burger and fries and a beer."< /text>

<Text>Let's be honest, you're going to pay quite a bit for a burger here, but the reason you're looking to eat here is to try exotic meat so you probably expect that. < review>
Great Burger spot serving a range of options from the classics to gourmet creations and burgers made from more exotic meats like ostrich or gator. They also have a decent selection of beer on tap to choose from.

I had a burger topped with bacon, pulled pork, and BBQ sauce which was delicious. Also tried the sweet potato fries which were pretty good as well. I will definitely be back.<//review>

< UserId.>
105154533692148157237< /UserId.>
<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
So many interesting choices, and they're all delicious! First, you can't go to Crazee Burger without an order of sweet potato fries. They are simply the best! For the main course, my boyfriend got the wild boar, which came with bacon, carmelized pears, and whipped cream! I ordered the gator burger topped with a curry sauce. We split them and agreed they were equally delicious, but for different reasons. The gator wasn't fancy. The flavors of the meat shone in this burger. The wild boar's fixings made for such a party on the pallette that we really couldn't taste the meat itself. We'll be back, though, to try even more from the menu!< /Review>

<review>Ate here 3/31/2019. The 1-start is strictly because this food establishment allows pets inside. I don't have a problem with properly trained legitimate service animals, but I do have a major problem when people feel the need to take their pet with them everywhere, especially restaurants and grocery stores. For one, I am allergic to dogs and cats. Two, there is a very real health and sanitation issue with pets being allowed where food is served. Aside from that, we were promptly greeted by a very friendly employee. She took our order. Food was delivered to our table. The food was hot, correct (as ordered) and delicious. The menu is far to 'hip' and 'trendy' for my style, but the signature burger and onion rings were very good, I would recommend. Not being native to San Diego, I don't really know the different neighborhoods. This seems like the, "Fabulous", part of town. Meaning, families or people with traditional family values, may not feel comfortable or ready to talk to their children about same sex relationships. Final thoughts. If you want a good burger, don't mind the environment or pets being where your food is prepared and served, then I would highly recommend this place. If you have issues with any of it, I would look elsewhere.< /review>< Pics>

{'time': 1562022625453, 'text': "Hi Picassini, whilst we appreciate you saying are burger are great, saying our portions have shrunk and perhaps we're getting greedy couldn't be farther from the truth. Our portion size across all menu items has been the same for over 8 years now (except for some sides which have increased in portion size). Our prices have increased over the past 8 years as well. Perhaps you don't live in the area anymore or are just ignorant of the price increases EVERY SINGLE BUSINESS has had to implement over the past 8 years due to things such as minimum wage increases, increased food cost, new taxes, etc. Even though we have increased our prices to try and offset these new costs we make less money every year (and believe me there's not much to begin with) to try and keep our prices as affordable as possible for our clientele.  In fact you can still come in for happy hour, EVERY SINGLE DAY, and get a burger, fries and a drink for $12.90. Or if you can't make happy hour come in at any time and get the same deal on the daily special. I wont tell you to go to any other business in the area and see how prices compare or even say you should go to McDonalds, the world standard for cheap burgers, and see how much their menu has increased over the last 8 years. Instead I would just like you to know that giving a mom and pop shop like ours a 3 star review and complaining about things you are clearly ignorant about hurts great establishments like ours who do our best to provide a great AFFORDABLE experience in today's volatile food and beverage industry."}<//resp>

I do, however, prefer that if a guest of ours does not like their particular burger that they give us a heads up before they leave so we can fix it right then and there.  The beauty of having an exotic option and a wide variety of meats on our menu, is also our greatest curse sometimes in that people may not like one of the exotic meats (as rare as this is, it does occasionally happen, and that's ok). I, myself, am not a fan of lamb because of the taste the meat offers.  That does not mean our lamb is not fresh, however.  It's just a different flavor that may not be for everyone.  That being said, to suggest that our lamb meat is not fresh is both incorrect and absurd.  We sell over 8000 burgers a month, so for us to not use fresh (and hand selected meat) is factually inaccurate.  We make the tzatziki sauce from scratch as well as make our half beef, half lamb patties here in this kitchen. I use Central Meat Company from down down and they have been around for over 100 years with the best meat you can get in San Diego.  You can trust me, I personally do all of the blind taste tests, along with help from my entire crew.  I have exceedingly high standards for food excellence and demand the greatest superiority in food quality as is possible for my establishment.  I apologize immensely  that we were not able to captivate you on your visit, and hope that you are willing to give us another shot. <username>Brian Bergstr√∂m<//username><Date>1338712199182</Date><rate>3<//rate>< Review>
Crazee Burger was good, but nothing extraordinary. I may or may not go back, it just depends.

I thought the prices were exorbitantly high for the unusual meats. I realize that everyplace doesn't sell ostrich, buffalo or gator. But enough places do. I enjoy ostrich at other burger places for half the price.

The house fries or whatever they called them were nothing special either, a sprinkling from the green can of Kraft Parmesan cheese, wow that really makes for special house fries.

As far as atmosphere, the place is a dive in what doesn't look like the best part of town... it's saving grace for us was the Police officers inside typing reports on their laptops. No food visible on their table, just computers. Maybe that was a sign...</Review>

<Resp>None< /Resp><name>Ray ‚ÄúStormageddon‚Äù Snoke< /name>< text>
This place offers a great vibe. If you're familiar with the area, this place fits right in. I've been there twice. The first time, a Saturday, we had to wait about 5 minutes for a place to sit. The second time was a Sunday, and there was plenty of seating available. Food came up quick both times, and was fantastic. Highly recommend the venison burger. Don't be put off by what they put onto the burger: the extra toppings really make the burgers! Only thing that keeps this from being a 5 star is the fact that their specialty burgers don't come with any fries. Then again, you're getting an unusual flavor for a pretty reasonable price, so I guess you can't have it all.< /text>

< Review>
First time going here and always wanted to try it hearing about its exotic menu of burgers. I decided to start my burgerventure off slow and rather than going straight to gator or kangaroo, i started with ostrich. They cut the ostrich with beef, which i knew a head of time, but figured it would a good first one. ....i wont get that one again, it was really dry (which i know can change with temp) but i didnt taste anything different. It was really bland so i figured id be able to taste the actual meat rather than seasonings, but again, just tasted beef.

I will be going again to try other burgers.

The customer service was amazing. Had a really good and friendly conversation with the gentleman at the register and he was just as friendly with the guests after me.

{'time': 1541222147986, 'text': "Hello Christopher,\nMy name is Garrett and I am the owner of Crazee Burger here in North Park.  Firstly, thank you for taking the time to leave us the feedback.  I have been the co-owner with another guy named Peter since the end of 2010.  So we are coming up on 9 years of ownership.  Unfortunately, the move blind-sided us and was a forced move type of situation.  It was neither preferred nor ideal for us.  I do want to point out, however, that we have remained virtually unchanged in both recipes and kitchen staff for quite some time now.  One thing is certain, I have never made a change that was not a vast improvement in quality.  I am, and have always been, unwilling to sacrifice quality in any capacity or circumstance, which is why I am so perplexed at your disapproval of the bread we use.  I spent 3 months consuming nothing but carbs on the seemingly never ending quest to find the best bakery in San Diego.  Alas, after months, I happened upon Bread and Cie.  At the time my mind was blown solely by their quality; by how amazingly fluffy, soft and moist their bread was compared to all of the other bakeries I tried.  It wasn't until after we began using them that I learned how profound their reputation was as demonstrated by how many awards and countless accolades they have received over the years. Perhaps, the cost of preservative free, baked fresh daily bread, is that it gets soggy more quickly than other bread.  I am honestly not sure, but this is the first unsatisfactory feedback I've received on the bread. Either way, there is a simple solution:  simply ask for the patty on the side and just before you are ready to eat the burger, place the patty on the bun with a fork.  Our meat is juicy and our bread is fresh so some soggy is going to be inevitable.\nIn regards to the kangaroo, we are as bummed as you are to not be able to offer it.  California (about 3 years ago) made it illegal to serve in the state.  That is completely out of our hands and was one of our best selling burgers.\nApologies for the long response.  Quality to me is second to nothing.. both in food and customer service. I sincerely hope that this long-winded response conveys how much I care about both my customers, and the feedback they leave.  I hope that you will give us another shot and maybe try my recommendation on your next visit. Thank you again Christopher.\nSincerely,\nGarrett"}</Response>

I am so sorry you were not impressed with our bratwurst.  Although, it is very popular and well liked, it is not a product we are necessarily known for.  We service close to 10 thousand customers a month, which, necessitates we change the oil more than regularly, so I assure you old oil is not used.  I suppose, considering that our onion rings are deep fried, it is impossible to avoid having grease with them. Our burgers are on another level, however.. We use a local meat company that grounds our house angus fresh daily. They use steak trim from briskets and new yorks. < text>
I've been here 3 times and I've just never really been impressed. Maybe I wanted to be and that's why I kept coming back. I've tried the wild boar, nacho cheese over angus beef, lamb, and salmon. None of them particularly stand out in my mind so I can't really recommend any of the burgers. The sweet potatoes fries are solid, though. Eat them with a mixture of their BBQ and mayonnaise sauce.

The staff is kind, the patrons are local, and the environment is no-nonsense. Come to think of it, that's probably why I wanted to like their food more. Normally that spells out a winner, but I was left desiring.< /text>

<user>109705978749187600531</user><Gmap_id>0x80deaadefc6abef7:0x4a64d785b6c70207</Gmap_id>< text>
Boy do I love a place where I can eat a KANGAROO or an ALLIGATOR, or even a boring old COW. It's a little pricey, but you are eating exotic meats, so while it may not be an every week choice, I do love going to either location. Having been to both, I think the decor in Old Town is better. North Park is crowded and old. But you can't beat the meat selection. You walk in, get in line and order, so there isn't a ton in the way of service. There are people who go around and clean and check up on people, but not a dedicated server, which I don't think is needed anyway. The people working there seem knowledgable about the meats. They are also honest in their assessments. I like it when a worker admits they don't like something. I hate the "everything is great!" response. I highly recommend Crazee Burger.<//text>

<rate>5< /rate><response>None< /response><userid>112283806801348458819<//userid><review>Killer burgers! I was pleasantly surprised. Even though they had me at "burgers" and moreso with "exotic meat options", my expectation was set at "novel, but not top notch." Happy to be proven wrong!  While I had planned on ordering the alligator patty, I was ultimately lured by some unusual toppings on a more traditional Angus patty--the Nopal Burger, topped with cactus leaf, avocado, and queso. While the guy who helped us said I could certainly substitute the Angus patty in that for an exotic meat, I appreciated his honest suggestion that I probably wouldn't be able to taste any significant difference with all the other flavors going on with that burger. The patty's were cooked to a perfect "medium", the toppings we're piled high, but not so high that I couldn't pick it up and eat it. <rating>3< /rating><text>Decent burgers, bit overpriced<//text>< resp>
{'time': 1555818616895, 'text': 'Hello Tomas,\nThank you for taking the time to leave us a review. I am sorry you felt we were overpriced.  The fact of the matter is that we are right on par for San Diego. To do business (especially as a brick and mortar restaurant) in San Diego is perhaps more expensive than one might think. We hand pick the finest ingredients for our burgers and have the best quality we absolutely can. We are confident we are offering a superior product (Bread and Cie bread, Central Meat black Angus steak trim ground beef). Finding this caliber of ingredients at almost any other place would be unlikely and probably cost more. Now obviously I could go into how much I pay for rent, product costs, material costs, utility costs, license and insurance fees, labor costs, payroll costs, repair and maintenance costs, product loss costs, bank fees, interests and principal payments, the increase in all of the aforementioned costs, and even the increasing invoice totals (due to the fact myriad other business are experiencing the same costs increase), but I will leave that to the imagination, as I am told to divulge that information is tacky and unprofessional.  If, however, you seek a lower price for our food, please feel free to check out our happy hour (which is offered 7 days a week 4 hours a day then again on friday and saturday from 9 to close).  We also have daily specials which are discounted combinations.  We also have punch cards we offer which is an added potential discount.  We do the best we can to keep our costs, and thustly, our prices as low as possible.  Hopefully we see you back during our promotional times, and thank you for understanding.'}< /resp>

<text>There needs to be better burger options in North Park, at least so that Crazy (or Crazee?) burger can at least step up their game. It's located perfectly in the heart of the neighborhood, but that's one of the only things they've got going for them.

Standard pricing for slightly above average hamburger fare. Buns are warm and toasty, cheese is always nicely melted, and meat (at least the ground beef) is fresh and cooked well (or medium well- whatever you like I suppose). Both regular fries and sweet potato fries are delicious and the portions are good.

Never dined here though, and don't have any desire to. The restaurant looks pretty grimey. If I were you, I'd order it and have it delivered over to Belching Beaver- have some cheap beer there and enjoy your food there.<//text>< pics>

< review>
THE place to go for a camel burger in North Park (tastes rather similar to beef, actually). With that I got the sidewinders, pictured, and albondigas soup. The sidewinders were nothing special-- no cajun seasoning or nothing-- and I thought the albondigas soup was really good, but it was actually my first albondigas soup, so I know nothing. All-in-all, the sides are nothing special. They do have a very good beer selection. But the main attraction here is the exotic meats-- I've had ostrich and bison,  and I think they even had some raptiles on the menu last time I was here. But if you just want a regular burger and fries, you'd be better off going to the Carl's Jr up the street.<//review>

<text>WOW to the Wild Boar Burger. wowowowow...what a truly delectable combination of sweet and savory piled into one giant mound of meat and toppings. It was recommended as the "most popular item" that has replaced the former fav, the Venison (it has the same toppings).

Awesome meat (cooked medium, the only way), bacon, mushrooms, poached red wine pear, cream and plum jelly = one outstanding and delicious meal. fan-friggin-tastic.

Also got the Santorini (greek style beef/lamb hybrid burger with tsatsiki) which was good...but pretty "standard" tasting. you come to crazee burger to get crazy, right?!?! but it was recommended as 2nd most popular, which is why we got it.

sweet potato fries with parmesan also quite good - thought *maybe* a bit overcooked.</text>< pics>

<response>{'time': 1427482088750, 'text': 'Hey Chad, Glad to see that you enjoyed our food! We take pride in providing a fresh, great tasting product and its always nice to hear when we succeed! Whilst we do our best to provide a great price on all of our product there are some things that are simply out of our control. Our exotic meats come from as far as Texas, Florida, Australia, New Zealand and other parts of the world. Due to the distance and rarity of the meats we get charged quite a bit to obtain them and therefore our prices reflect that. The "a la carte add ons" are quite popular with the majority of people due to the fact that if you don\'t want cheese or avocado on your burger you don\'t have to pay for it only to ask to have it removed. Even with our extremely high food cost we actually offer happy hour to our patrons 7 days a week totaling more happy hours then "regular" hours. On happy hour you can get a fresh ground 6oz. angus burger with cheese, fries and a soda for only $9.67. Hopefully now knowing the difference between the "price" and the "value" of our product will help you not to think of our exotic burgers as a "joke" but as a great way to enjoy a quality meal in a north park landmark establishment.'}<//response>< Rate>

< review>
This place is good, but I cannot give it more than 3 stars.

The good:  the burgers are great and they have a helluva selection with their exotic meats.  I think their Texas and Santorini burgers are off the hook.

The bad:  the only thing crazee about this place are their prices.  They don't offer cheese on any of their ridiculously priced burgers. I mean C'mon man, really?

They ONLY offer a large plate of fries a la carte at a price tag of $2.50 that I guarantee a majority of the ppl eating these fries do not finish.

I payed a hefty $13.90 for a Santorini w/cheese, fries and a diet coke.  I can't complain about the food, except I don't think their fries are all that great esp. Given the price.  Then they expect you to tip them after they sucker punch you to the gut.

I have never even tried their exotic meats like kangaroo or antelope because quite frankly $13-$14 bucks for a burger is a joke.  Then u have to add everything else along with it.

Great burgers, but there are plenty of burger joints that offer good quality without the headaches of a la carte add ons.

I will only go back when I am with someone to share fries and split a 2/3rd lb'er.. No more solo trips for me.</review>
< Name>
Chad King<//Name>

The "a la carte add ons" are quite popular with the majority of people due to the fact that if you don\'t want cheese or avocado on your burger you don\'t have to pay for it only to ask to have it removed. Even with our extremely high food cost we actually offer happy hour to our patrons 7 days a week totaling more happy hours then "regular" hours.
